[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m You'll need the following Python packages:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```bash
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m pip install boto3 numpy pandas scikit-learn xgboost shap
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Your environment needs AWS credentials configured (via environment variables, an instance profile, or `~/.aws/credentials`). The IAM role or user needs:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `sagemaker:InvokeEndpoint`
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `healthlake:SearchWithGet`, `healthlake:ReadResource`
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:GetItem`
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `cloudwatch:PutMetricData`
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m For local development and testing (which is what this example does), you only need `numpy`, `pandas`, `scikit-learn`, `xgboost`, and `shap`. The boto3 calls are shown but wrapped so you can run the core logic without an AWS account.
